REMARKS: After takeoff, MP saw three large birds directly in his flight path.  The MP saw two birds dive down to avoid the aircraft while the other leveled off.  The MP executed an evasive maneuver, but the third bird impacted the aircraft.  Post-flight revealed extensive damage to the right inlet, engine, and conformal fuel tank.  It appears that part of the bird was split in half by the lower intake lip.  Impact point created a hole on the lower intake lip and ramp.  Half the bird went into the engine and half skipped off the right conformal fuel tank impacting the lower right wing surface and weapons pylons.  The majority of the bird went down the intake, impacting the first stage of the engine fan.  It damaged several first and second stage fan blades.

MISSION WAS PLANNED AND FLOWN AS A 2-SHIP FORMATION TACTICAL LOW LEVEL TRAINING SORTIE IN THE 137AW LATNA.  AFTER COMPLETING THE FORMATION PROTION OF THE FLIGHT, THE BIRD STRIKE AIRCRAFT ENTERED THE VISUAL TRAFFIC PATTERN FOR A PILOT SHORTFIELD LANDING EVALUATION.  BIRD STRIKE AIRCREW DID NOT SEE BIRD PRIOR TO STRIKE BUT HEARD BIRD IMPACT ON AIRCRAFT.  EVENT AIRCREW QUICKLY ASSESSED ENGINE INDICATIONS WHICH WERE NORMAL, AND CONTINUED APPROACH AND UNEVENTFUL FULL-STOP LANDING TO 3,090' LONG ASSAULT ZONE.  CONTACTED MDS QUALIFIED MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WHO MET THE AIRCRAFT ON THE ANG PARKING RAMP FOR VISUAL INSPECTION OF AIRCRAFT.  MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL DETERMINED THERE WAS NO PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO AIRCRAFT AND RELEASED IT FOR CONTINUED FLIGHT BY FOLLOW-ON AIRCREW. THE FOLLOWING DAY DURING MAINTENANCE PREFLIGHT BPO INSPECTIONS, BIRD REMAINS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF THE NOSE RADOME (IMPACT POINT 1) AND THE TOP OF THE FUSELAGE (IMPACT POINT 2) ABOVE THE COCKPIT.  RADOME REMAINS APPEAR TO BE Falco sparverius, American Kestrel.  COMMON TO THE AREA AND INVOLVED IN PREVIOUS BIRD STRIKES AT KOKC.
